aDf(a,b){if(b<8)return'Near black. Avoid Mars Black or Ivory Black straight from the tube for shadows \u2014 they create lifeless, "hole" darks. Instead, mix Ultramarine Blue + Burnt Umber for a rich, colour-temperature-flexible dark (warm it by adding more Umber; cool it by adding more Ultramarine). Alternatively, Phthalo Green + Alizarin Crimson creates a deep, transparent, luminous near-black excellent for glazing darks.'
if(b>92)return"Near white. Use Titanium-Zinc White (blend of Titanium and Zinc White) \u2014 it is less chalky than pure Titanium and less fragile than pure Zinc. For warm highlights (sunlight, skin highlights): add a speck of Cadmium Yellow Pale or Naples Yellow. For cool highlights (moonlight, snow in shadow, chrome): add a touch of Cerulean Blue or Cobalt Blue. Never use raw Zinc White in lower layers \u2014 it is brittle when dry."
if(b<30)return"Dark neutral grey. Mix Ultramarine Blue + Burnt Sienna in roughly equal proportions, then adjust temperature: more blue = cooler grey, more sienna = warmer. Add Titanium White to raise the value. This gives a far livelier grey than Ivory Black + White. Paynes Grey (pre-mixed blue-grey) is a useful convenience colour but can look flat if over-relied upon."
if(b>70)return"Light neutral grey. Mix Titanium-Zinc White with a tiny amount of Ultramarine Blue + an equally tiny amount of Burnt Sienna or Yellow Ochre to control temperature. A pure-white + black mix always looks flat and chalky. To make a warm light grey: more ochre, less blue. To make a cool light grey: more blue, less ochre."
return"Mid neutral grey. Mix Ultramarine Blue + Burnt Sienna + Titanium White \u2014 the classic trio for neutral greys. Shift temperature with more Ultramarine (cool) or Burnt Sienna (warm). Chromatic greys made this way are far more vibrant than Ivory Black + White, which produce dead, lifeless mixtures. Paynes Grey can supplement but should not be the sole mixer."},
