B.YP=new A.dc(345,10,"Warm Red","Reach for Cadmium Red Medium or Pyrrole Red \u2014 both are warm, orange-leaning reds with high opacity. Cadmium Red is the classic choice for flesh tones and bold, sunlit passages. Pyrrole Red (PR254) is a modern, non-toxic alternative with comparable warmth and excellent lightfastness.","Darken with Alizarin Crimson or Quinacridone Rose (pulls the red cooler and deeper without muddying it), or add a tiny touch of Viridian (the true complement of red) for a rich chromatic dark. Avoid Ivory Black \u2014 it shifts warm reds toward brown-purple and deadens them.","At mid-value, Cadmium Red stands on its own. Mix with Cadmium Orange to push warmer or with a sliver of Alizarin Crimson to deepen the hue without losing saturation.","Lighten with Titanium-Zinc White (less chalky than pure Titanium). Warm reds lose vibrancy fast with white \u2014 compensate by adding a tiny amount of Cadmium Orange or Cadmium Red Light back into the tint to restore warmth. Avoid Zinc White alone \u2014 it cools and greys the red.","Knock back saturation with a small amount of Viridian (its complement) or Yellow Ochre for an earthy, sun-baked red. Raw Umber gives a very muted, shadow-like red-brown. Add in tiny increments \u2014 it goes brown fast.","Use Cadmium Red or Pyrrole Red straight from the tube. Keep the palette clean and avoid contaminating with blues or purples. Apply in single, confident strokes \u2014 repeated working-over greys the paint.")
B.YG=new A.dc(10,22,"Red-Orange","Mix Cadmium Red Light with a small amount of Cadmium Yellow Medium \u2014 roughly 3 parts red to 1 part yellow as a starting point. Alternatively, use Cadmium Red Light alone (it already leans orange) or try Pyrrole Orange (PO73) for a single-pigment solution with exceptional transparency and vibrancy.","Darken with Burnt Sienna \u2014 it shares the red-orange family and deepens without shifting the hue dramatically. For a richer dark, add Transparent Red Oxide (cleaner than Burnt Sienna). Avoid black entirely.","Burnt Sienna can serve as a mid-value red-orange straight from the tube. Strengthen with Cadmium Red or Pyrrole Orange as needed.","Add Titanium-Zinc White cautiously \u2014 it cools quickly. Compensate by leaning the mix toward Cadmium Yellow Deep before adding white, which keeps the warmth as the value rises.","A tiny touch of Cerulean Blue (its nearest complement) mutes red-orange toward a warm terra-cotta. Yellow Ochre is a safer, less risky desaturant for subtle adjustments.","Use Cadmium Red Light + Cadmium Yellow Medium, both near full strength. These cadmiums are both warm, so no cool third primary creeps in to dull the mixture.")
B.YT=new A.dc(22,38,"Orange","Pure orange: mix Cadmium Red Light (1 part) with Cadmium Yellow Medium (2 parts) \u2014 both warm pigments, so no third primary interferes. Cadmium Orange is a reliable single-pigment alternative. For a more transparent orange, try Pyrrole Orange. Avoid mixing a cool red (Alizarin) with a cool yellow (Lemon) \u2014 the result will be a muted, brownish orange.","Use Burnt Sienna to deepen, or add a very small touch of Ultramarine Blue (its complement) for a rich, chromatic shadow. Transparent Red Oxide is excellent for deep, warm-orange shadows.","Cadmium Orange at mid-value is already powerful. Dilute toward yellow or red as needed. Burnt Sienna is a natural mid-value earthy orange.","Mix Cadmium Orange with Cadmium Yellow Pale before adding white \u2014 this prevents the tint from going beige or chalky. A Titanium-Zinc blend is gentler than pure Titanium White.","Add a drop of Ultramarine Blue to shift toward a burnt, earthy orange. Yellow Ochre mixed with Cadmium Red gives a naturally muted, terracotta-like orange without risk of over-greying.","Commit to Cadmium Red Light + Cadmium Yellow Medium and mix fully until uniform. Use straight from the palette; avoid layering extra pigments \u2014 orange is at maximum punch with just two warm pigments.")
B.YO=new A.dc(38,50,"Amber / Yellow-Orange","Mix Cadmium Yellow Deep with a touch of Cadmium Red Light, or use Yellow Ochre with a small addition of Burnt Sienna for a more natural, earth-tone amber. Naples Yellow is a useful pre-mixed warm yellow-orange for luminous, historically authentic skin and warm-light passages.","Deepen with Burnt Sienna, Transparent Red Oxide, or a very small touch of Burnt Umber for rich, golden-shadow tones. Raw Umber cools it more than Burnt Umber.","Yellow Ochre sits naturally in this hue family at mid-value \u2014 it is an ideal single-pigment starting point for amber tones.","Add Titanium-Zinc White plus a little Cadmium Yellow to prevent the tint going chalky. Naples Yellow behaves well here as a pre-lightened amber.","Yellow Ochre is already a muted amber. If starting from Cadmium Yellow + Cadmium Red, add a touch of Raw Umber to tone it to an earthy gold without going brown.","Cadmium Yellow Deep + Cadmium Red Light kept at full tube strength. This zone has a naturally warm, high-energy tone \u2014 mixes are punchy without further effort.")
B.YL=new A.dc(50,62,"Warm Yellow","Cadmium Yellow Medium is the benchmark: warm, powerful, opaque. Cadmium Yellow Deep pushes toward amber. For a transparent warm yellow (e.g. glazing highlights), Hansa Yellow Medium (PY97) is excellent \u2014 cleaner than Cadmium in masstone, brilliant as a tint.","Darken yellow by mixing in Yellow Ochre or Raw Sienna \u2014 this keeps the hue family intact. A touch of Burnt Sienna makes a golden-shadow colour. Never darken yellow with black \u2014 it turns green instantly.","Cadmium Yellow Medium at mid-value. Naples Yellow sits in this range as a useful pre-mixed warm yellow-cream.","Yellow is the hardest colour to lighten \u2014 adding white makes it chalky and pale quickly. The best approach: use the yellow at a higher-key value to begin with (Cadmium Yellow Pale or Lemon Yellow), and add only a tiny speck of white for the very lightest highlights.","Add a small touch of Violet (Dioxazine Purple or Ultramarine) \u2014 the complement of yellow \u2014 to knock back intensity without shifting the hue excessively. Yellow Ochre is a naturally muted yellow for earthy passages.","Cadmium Yellow Medium or Hansa Yellow, unmixed, are among the most saturated yellows available. Apply with confidence \u2014 mixing with anything dulls yellow faster than most other hues.")
B.YM=new A.dc(62,76,"Cool / Lemon Yellow","Lemon Yellow (Cadmium Lemon) or Hansa Yellow Light (PY3 or PY74) \u2014 both have a greenish-cool bias. Hansa Yellow Light is the more transparent and colour-pure option; Cadmium Lemon is opaque and strong. This yellow is essential for mixing clean, bright greens \u2014 it contains no hidden red that would muddy the mixture.","Darken with Sap Green, a sliver of Viridian, or Yellow Ochre. Avoid black at all costs \u2014 it produces a dull, dead olive.","A mix of Hansa Yellow Light and a touch of Sap Green gives a natural mid-value yellow-green. ","Add a very small amount of Titanium-Zinc White, or better still, use Cadmium Lemon at near-full strength which is already quite light. Naples Yellow (warm) will shift the hue warmer if added for lightening.","A touch of Dioxazine Purple (use a speck \u2014 very powerful) or Cobalt Violet will quietly desaturate the cool yellow toward ochre. Be extremely careful \u2014 yellow loses chroma fast.","Hansa Yellow Light or Cadmium Lemon, unmixed. When painting sunlit foliage or bright highlights, lay this down pure and let it sing \u2014 any additional pigment reduces its clarity.")
B.YS=new A.dc(76,90,"Yellow-Green / Chartreuse","Mix Lemon Yellow or Hansa Yellow Light with a tiny touch of Phthalo Green (Blue Shade) \u2014 use a speck of Phthalo (it is extremely powerful). Alternatively, Sap Green + Cadmium Yellow Light. This is the most luminous zone of the colour wheel, found in spring foliage and sunlit grass.","Deepen with Sap Green, Viridian, or a touch of Burnt Umber. A sliver of Cadmium Red (the complement) gives a natural, shadowed chartreuse without going brown.","Sap Green + Cadmium Yellow Medium is a natural mid-value here. Oxide of Chromium (opaque muted green) + Yellow gives an earthy variant.","Add Lemon Yellow rather than white \u2014 this raises value while keeping the vibrancy. If white is needed, use sparingly and re-add a touch of yellow to restore the cool-green note.","Add a touch of Burnt Sienna, Cadmium Red Light, or Alizarin Crimson to soften and earth the chartreuse toward olive.","Lemon Yellow + a speck of Phthalo Green, both at maximum strength. This zone is inherently high-chroma \u2014 apply with single strokes.")
B.YJ=new A.dc(90,110,"Warm Spring Green","Mix Cadmium Yellow Medium with Phthalo Green (Blue Shade) or Viridian \u2014 adjust ratio for the warmth needed (more yellow = warmer). Sap Green is a ready-made warm green; mix it with Cadmium Yellow to push it brighter. This is the most common foliage green in landscape painting.","Deepen with Viridian + a touch of Alizarin Crimson (a classic shadow green that keeps the colour alive). Alternatively, Phthalo Green + a tiny touch of Cadmium Red gives a rich, dark spring green.","Sap Green sits naturally here at mid-value. Warm it with Yellow Ochre or lighten with Cadmium Yellow. Oxide of Chromium is a useful mid-value opaque green for painting en plein air.","Lighten with Cadmium Yellow or Lemon Yellow \u2014 far better than white for greens. White cools and greys greens significantly.","Add Burnt Sienna or Raw Umber for a natural olive. Yellow Ochre + Ultramarine Blue gives a sophisticated, earthy warm green without ever touching a tube of green paint.","Phthalo Green (speck) + Cadmium Yellow Medium at full strength. This mix is aggressive \u2014 build it cautiously.")
B.YV=new A.dc(110,135,"Mid Green","Viridian (PG18) is the classic mid-green \u2014 transparent, cool, and historically durable. Mix with Cadmium Yellow Medium for warmth or Cerulean for a cooler, bluer green. Phthalo Green (Yellow Shade, PG36) is a more powerful, warmer alternative. Oxide of Chromium (PG17) provides a muted, opaque mid-green excellent for solid coverage in foliage.","Darken with Phthalo Green + a touch of Alizarin Crimson or Burnt Umber. Viridian alone is too transparent for deep shadows \u2014 switch to Phthalo Green as the shadow green.","Viridian at mid-strength, possibly warmed with Yellow Ochre. Sap Green is a reliable mid-value workhorse here.","Lighten green with yellow first (Cadmium Yellow or Hansa Yellow), not white. White greys and cools greens dramatically. Only use white for the very palest tints (mist, haze).","A touch of Cadmium Red or Burnt Sienna desaturates mid-green toward a natural, earthy sage. Terre Verte (earth green) is a single-pigment muted green ideal for underpainting foliage.","Viridian or Phthalo Green with Cadmium Yellow \u2014 keep the palette clean and apply without over-working. Overworked greens go grey.")
B.YR=new A.dc(135,155,"Cool / Deep Green","Phthalo Green Blue Shade (PG7) \u2014 one of the most powerful pigments in the oil painter's arsenal. Use a speck: it has extraordinary tinting strength and stains rapidly. Viridian + Prussian Blue gives a deep, cool green. Cerulean Blue + Cadmium Yellow makes a softer, cooler green.","Phthalo Green + Dioxazine Purple or Alizarin Crimson gives near-black shadow greens used widely for deep foliage and water. Phthalo Green + Burnt Umber creates a very dark, naturalistic green.","Phthalo Green (tiny amount) + Cadmium Yellow Medium is the most luminous entry to this zone. Oxide of Chromium is a restrained opaque alternative at mid-value.","Add Lemon Yellow or Hansa Yellow Light. Phthalo Green is so dark in masstone that significant yellow is needed before it reads green rather than black. Do not add white until the yellow has done its work.","Mix in Burnt Umber or Raw Umber. A touch of Cadmium Red Light will also shift the cool green toward a natural woodland shadow.","Phthalo Green is inherently vibrant \u2014 it may need calming (see above). For a vivid, cool green, try Viridian + Cadmium Lemon, which is slightly less aggressive than Phthalo.")
B.YN=new A.dc(155,172,"Blue-Green / Warm Teal","Mix Viridian with Cerulean Blue, or Phthalo Green with Cobalt Blue. Cerulean Blue itself already sits in this range. Cobalt Turquoise (PB36) is an excellent single-pigment teal, semi-opaque and beautifully luminous for water and shallow-sea painting.","Deepen with Phthalo Green + Ultramarine Blue, or Viridian + a touch of Alizarin Crimson. Phthalo Green + Dioxazine Purple creates extraordinary deep-water darks.","Cerulean Blue at mid-value is naturally in this range. Cobalt Turquoise is an excellent mid-value single-pigment option.","Add Titanium-Zinc White or lighten with Cadmium Lemon (pushes it greener). Cerulean tints are naturally light and airy \u2014 it responds well to white without going chalky.","A tiny touch of Burnt Sienna (the complement) desaturates toward a natural grey-teal. Useful for distant water and overcast seascapes.","Cobalt Turquoise or Cerulean Blue + Viridian, applied directly. Avoid overmixing on canvas \u2014 place separate strokes of each and let the eye blend them.")
B.YK=new A.dc(172,190,"Teal / Cyan","Mix Phthalo Blue (Green Shade, PB15:3) with Phthalo Green (Blue Shade, PG7) \u2014 both transparent, both extremely powerful. Use tiny amounts of each. Cobalt Turquoise is a safer, less intense single-pigment option. Manganese Blue Hue offers a softer alternative.","Phthalo Blue + Phthalo Green + Dioxazine Purple makes an extraordinary deep teal-black for water and tropical shadows. Prussian Blue + Phthalo Green is another classic deep.","Cobalt Turquoise sits naturally here. Phthalo mixtures need to be built up from very small starting amounts.","Add Titanium White \u2014 cyan tints are among the most beautiful in oil painting. A sliver of Cerulean Blue in the tint prevents it from going cold and lifeless.","A touch of Burnt Sienna or Raw Sienna knocks back the intensity toward a grey-green for atmospheric perspective.","Phthalo Blue + Phthalo Green is one of the most intense colour combinations possible \u2014 applied at full strength it rivals the saturation of tropical water photography.")
B.YW=new A.dc(190,210,"Cerulean / Sky Blue",'Cerulean Blue (PB35 or PB36) is the definitive sky blue \u2014 semi-opaque, with a distinctive green undertone that reads as "sky" more naturally than any other pigment. Mix with Titanium White for classic sky gradations. Cobalt Blue + a touch of Viridian approximates Cerulean if needed.',"Darken sky blue with Ultramarine Blue (warms and deepens it) or add a touch of Burnt Sienna for a greyed, overcast-sky tone. Avoid black \u2014 it deadens sky colour and adds green-grey.","Cerulean Blue at mid-value is a natural sky at mid-day. Cobalt Blue is slightly deeper and slightly warmer for the upper sky.","Add Titanium-Zinc White \u2014 Cerulean lightens beautifully. For the palest horizon sky, add a tiny touch of Cadmium Lemon to warm the tint back from cold-white.","Mix Cerulean with Raw Umber or Burnt Sienna for atmospheric, hazy sky tones and distant hills. A sliver of complementary orange gives a dignified, restrained grey-blue.","Cerulean or Cobalt Blue applied at near full strength for a deep midday sky. Phthalo Blue + white is more intense but less naturalistic \u2014 save it for tropical settings.")
B.YQ=new A.dc(210,228,"Cobalt Blue","Cobalt Blue (PB28) is the most balanced blue on the palette \u2014 neither warm nor cool in a strong sense, transparent, and with a subtlety that Phthalo and Ultramarine lack. It is the benchmark blue for portraiture and neutral skies. Mix with white for a faithful, luminous mid-blue.","Deepen with Ultramarine Blue or a small touch of Dioxazine Purple. Avoid black \u2014 Cobalt + Burnt Umber gives a rich neutral dark.","Cobalt Blue at mid-value. A touch of Viridian pushes it slightly cooler; a touch of Alizarin Crimson pushes it slightly warmer.","Cobalt + Titanium-Zinc White tints softly and naturalistically. Do not add too much white at once \u2014 Cobalt is a weak tinter and goes pale quickly. Build up in thin layers.","A touch of Burnt Sienna (its complement) gives a restrained, atmospheric grey-blue. Yellow Ochre is a gentle alternative for subtle desaturation.","Cobalt Blue cannot achieve the same intensity as Phthalo or Ultramarine. For maximum saturation, apply it pure with minimal white, and accept its inherently refined, luminous quality.")
B.YU=new A.dc(228,248,"Ultramarine Blue",'Ultramarine Blue (PB29) has a violet undertone \u2014 making it the "warmest" blue and the best choice for mixing clean purples and deep evening shadows. It is semi-transparent with high tinting strength. The classic blue for portrait shadows, deep skies, and purple mixtures. Mix Ultramarine + Burnt Sienna for a full range of darks.',"Ultramarine + Burnt Umber gives rich, nearly black darks that are alive with colour. Adding a touch of Alizarin Crimson deepens and enriches the shadow further. This combination (UM + BU) is one of the most useful in oil painting.","Ultramarine at mid-value. Mix with Burnt Sienna for neutrals, with Cobalt Blue for a softer mid-blue, or with Cadmium Lemon for an atmospheric grey-green.","Lighten with Titanium White \u2014 Ultramarine tints beautifully toward periwinkle and lavender. For a warmer tint, add a touch of Alizarin Crimson before adding white.","Add Burnt Sienna (complement) for restrained blue tones. A grey-blue for shadow passages can be made entirely from Ultramarine + Burnt Sienna + white, no black needed.","Use Ultramarine at near full strength. It is inherently a deep, powerful blue \u2014 apply it without hesitation for zenith skies and deep shadow accents.")
B.YD=new A.dc(248,262,"Phthalo Blue / Cool Blue","Phthalo Blue (Green Shade, PB15:3) \u2014 extraordinarily powerful and transparent. A speck goes an immense distance. It leans toward green, making it ideal for bright, cool passages. Phthalo Blue (Red Shade, PB15:1) leans slightly toward violet and is better for purple mixtures. Use with great care \u2014 it stains and dominates mixes instantly.","Phthalo Blue + Dioxazine Purple + a touch of Burnt Umber gives extraordinary, near-black darks with a cool, luminous depth. Prussian Blue is a single-pigment deep cool blue for shadows.","Phthalo Blue is so strong in masstone it reads almost black. Significant amounts of white or yellow are needed before it even reads as blue. Build up from tiny starting amounts.","Phthalo Blue + Titanium White gives a clean, vivid sky blue. Use a tiny speck of Phthalo \u2014 start with more white than you think you need, then add Phthalo incrementally.","A touch of Burnt Sienna (its complement) desaturates toward a steel-grey-blue. Phthalo Blue loses saturation faster than Ultramarine when mixed with earth tones.","Phthalo Blue is one of the most intense pigments available. For maximum brightness, mix with white only. Avoid adding any warm pigment \u2014 even a trace of orange or umber will noticeably dull it.")
B.YC=new A.dc(262,278,"Blue-Violet","Mix Ultramarine Blue with a small amount of Dioxazine Purple (PV23) \u2014 Dioxazine is the most powerful purple available; use a speck. Alternatively, Ultramarine Blue + Quinacridone Violet gives a slightly warmer, more transparent blue-violet. Cobalt Blue + Alizarin Crimson gives a softer variant.","Deepen with Dioxazine Purple alone (it is already very dark). Ultramarine + Dioxazine + Burnt Umber = one of the richest near-blacks possible \u2014 use for the deepest portrait shadows.","Ultramarine + Dioxazine at mid-value. A sliver of Alizarin Crimson warms and enriches the mixture.","Add Titanium White \u2014 blue-violets tint to beautiful lavender tones. A touch of Quinacridone Rose in the tint prevents it from going chalky-grey.","A tiny touch of Yellow Ochre (the complement of violet) softens the blue-violet toward a dusty, sophisticated grey-purple.","Ultramarine Blue + Dioxazine Purple (careful with proportion \u2014 Dioxazine is extraordinarily powerful). This combination is used for deep, luminous twilight and shadow passages.")
B.YF=new A.dc(278,296,"Violet / Purple","The cleanest violet: Alizarin Crimson (or Quinacridone Red) + Ultramarine Blue. Both pigments lean toward each other on the colour wheel, so no yellow is introduced that would muddy the mixture. Critical: do NOT use Cadmium Red (contains yellow, muddies purple) or Phthalo Blue (green undertone kills the violet). Dioxazine Purple (PV23) is a powerful single-pigment violet.","Deepen with Dioxazine Purple, or add more Ultramarine Blue. A touch of Burnt Umber will create a deep, natural purple-brown useful for shadow areas.","Alizarin Crimson + Ultramarine at equal parts. Cobalt Violet (semi-transparent) is an expensive but exquisite mid-value violet that mixes more softly than Dioxazine.","Add Titanium-Zinc White plus a touch of Quinacridone Rose to keep the tint from going grey. Cobalt Violet tints to a beautiful, luminous mauve.","A small addition of Yellow Ochre gently pulls violet toward grey-purple \u2014 useful for atmospheric shadow tones. Raw Umber gives a deeper, earthier desaturation.","Alizarin Crimson + Ultramarine Blue, well-mixed, at near-full strength. These two pigments create one of the richest mixtures possible precisely because neither contains the third primary.")
B.YH=new A.dc(296,314,"Red-Purple / Magenta","Quinacridone Magenta (PV19 or PR122) is the definitive pigment here \u2014 transparent, extremely lightfast, and brilliantly saturated. It replaced the less lightfast Alizarin in modern palettes for this colour range. Mix with Ultramarine or Dioxazine to push deeper into purple; mix with Quinacridone Red to move toward rose.","Deepen with Dioxazine Purple or Ultramarine Blue. Avoid black and brown \u2014 they dull Quinacridone's brilliant transparency.","Quinacridone Magenta straight from the tube at mid-value. It is highly staining \u2014 use small amounts and build up.","Add Titanium-Zinc White \u2014 Quinacridone Magenta tints to extraordinary, glowing pinks and roses. It lightens better than Alizarin Crimson with much greater lightfastness.","A touch of Sap Green (its complement) will reduce intensity toward a dignified dusty mauve. Raw Umber gives a deeper, more earthy desaturation.","Quinacridone Magenta at full strength is electrifying. Apply with single confident strokes. It is one of the most saturated pigments in the oil painter's range.")
B.YE=new A.dc(314,330,"Rose / Pink","Rose Madder Genuine (PR9) for a soft, traditional rose \u2014 but it has limited lightfastness. The modern substitute is Quinacridone Rose (PV19) \u2014 transparent, lightfast, exquisite. Mix Quinacridone Rose with Titanium-Zinc White for a range of luminous pinks that cannot be matched by any other pigment. A tiny touch of Cadmium Red Light warms the rose toward salmon.","Deepen rose with Alizarin Crimson or Quinacridone Magenta, or add Ultramarine Blue for a cool, deep dusky-rose. Avoid black \u2014 it produces a muddy, lifeless dusty rose.","Quinacridone Rose at mid-value. For skin-tone passages, mix Quinacridone Rose + Yellow Ochre + Titanium White \u2014 a reliable, luminous flesh base.","Quinacridone Rose + Titanium-Zinc White creates brilliant pinks. For the palest, most delicate tints (petals, infant skin, dawn light), use a very large amount of white with just a speck of rose.","A touch of Sap Green or Yellow Ochre will gently neutralise the rose toward a dusty, vintage pink \u2014 excellent for aged fabrics, faded flowers, and shadow passages.","Quinacridone Rose at near-full strength is one of the most beautiful pigments in oil. Apply it boldly for florals, sunsets, and bold colourful passages.")
B.YI=new A.dc(330,345,"Cool Red / Crimson","Quinacridone Red (PR209) is the modern, lightfast cool red \u2014 transparent and clean. Alizarin Crimson (PR83) is the traditional choice \u2014 cool, transparent, deeply staining \u2014 but has known lightfastness concerns (especially in tints). Permanent Alizarin Crimson offers the hue with improved durability. This is the essential red for mixing clean violets and purples.","Deepen with Dioxazine Purple or Ultramarine Blue \u2014 this pushes toward a deep, rich burgundy or wine. A touch of Viridian (complement) gives a deep chromatic neutral.","Alizarin or Quinacridone Red at mid-value, possibly with a speck of Cadmium Red to warm slightly.","Add Titanium-Zinc White \u2014 cool reds tint to a beautiful crimson-pink. For lightfastness, always prefer Quinacridone Red over Alizarin Crimson in tints.","A small addition of Viridian or Sap Green (the complement of cool red) desaturates to a deep grey-red. Useful for shadowed flesh and aged red fabrics.","Quinacridone Red or Alizarin Crimson at near-full strength. These transparent reds are best used in glazes over a dry underpainting for maximum depth and luminosity.")
